"Barros N., Salgado J., Villanueva M., Rodriquez-Añón J., Proupin J., Feijóo S., Martín-Pastor M.","Application of DSC-TG and NMR to study the soil organic matter",2011,"Journal of Thermal Analysis and Calorimetry","104","1",,"53","60",,,10.1007/s10973-010-1163-4,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79953171107&partnerID=40&md5=cd336b69f67ba10ca5b8826063e4aa70","Department of Applied Physics, Faculty of Physics, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Unidad de Resonancia Magnética, RIAIDT, Edif. Cactus, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, Spain","Barros, N., Department of Applied Physics, Faculty of Physics, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Salgado, J., Department of Applied Physics, Faculty of Physics, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Villanueva, M., Department of Applied Physics, Faculty of Physics, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Rodriquez-Añón, J., Department of Applied Physics, Faculty of Physics, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Proupin, J., Department of Applied Physics, Faculty of Physics, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Feijóo, S., Department of Applied Physics, Faculty of Physics, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, Spain; Martín-Pastor, M., Unidad de Resonancia Magnética, RIAIDT, Edif. Cactus, University of Santiago de Compostela, Santiago de Compostela, Spain","The environmental concern on soil exploitation, linked to global warming by the Kyoto protocol, is responsible for increasing interest in the understanding of the role of the composition and structure of the soil organic matter (SOM) on soil carbon, C, dynamics. Thermal analysis and nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) are applied to study the thermal properties, the structure and composition of the SOM of six samples with different C contents in order to improve the interpretation of results given by thermal analysis. Results showed that the direct integral of the combustion peaks obtained by DSC and the percentage of SOM given by TG were both directly related to the quantity of total soil C. Thus, soils with higher C content showed higher energy content too. The combustion temperatures of the curves given by DSC are those reported for labile OM. NMR results indicated the presence of aliphatic C, carbohydrates, and a weak signal in the aromatic C band in all the samples that was not detected in the DSC curves. Only two samples showed carboxyl/carbonyl C which was not detected by DSC also. © Akadémiai Kiadó, Budapest, Hungary 2010.","NMR; Soil organic matter; Thermal analysis","C-bands; Combustion temperatures; DSC curves; Energy content; Environmental concerns; KYOTO protocol; NMR; Soil carbon; Soil organic matter; Soil organic matters; Thermal analysis; Thermal properties; Weak signals; Biogeochemistry; Biological materials; Carbohydrates; Combustion; Emission control; Global warming; Resonance; Soils; Thermoanalysis; Thermodynamic properties; Nuclear magnetic resonance",,,,,,"Schlesinger, W.H., Andrews, J.A., Soil respiration and the global carbon cycle (2007) Biogeochemistry, 48, pp. 7-20. , 10.1023/A:1006247623877; Dumanski, J., Carbon sequestration, soil conservation, and the Kyoto protocol: Summary of implications (2004) Climatic Change, 65 (3), pp. 255-261. , DOI 10.1023/B:CLIM.0000038210.66057.61; Barros, N., Salgado, J., Rodríguez-Añón, J.A., Proupín, J., Villanueva, M., Hansen, L.D., Calorimetric approach to metabolic carbon conversion efficiency in soils: Comparison of experimental and theoretical models (2010) J Therm Anal Calorim, 99, pp. 771-777. , 10.1007/s10973-010-0673-4 1:CAS:528:DC%2BC3cXjt1elt7k%3D; Gartzia-Bengoetxea, N., González-Arias, A., Merino, A., Arano De, I.M., Soil organic matter in soil physical fractions in adjacent semi-natural and cultivated stands in te